data.name: ArtifactType
data.value: Describes the object type associated with a particular Artifact. Example types include: !App, !Class, !Instance, etc.

data.name: CrowdianType
data.value: Describes the level of access and control given to a particular Crowdian. Example types include: Invite, !Member, Admin, etc.

data.name: DescriptorType
data.value: Provides meaning (via Descriptor) to the relationship between the two Artifacts in a particular Factor. Example types include: Is A, Refers To, Sounds Like, etc.

data.name: DirectorAction
data.value: Describes an action to be taken (via Director) on one of the two Artifacts in a particular Factor. Example actions include: Read, Learn, Obtain, etc.

data.name: DirectorType
data.value: Provides meaning (via Director) to the directional connection between the two Artifacts in a particular Factor. Example types include: Hyperlink, Suggested Path, Defined Path, etc.

data.name: EventorPrecision
data.value: Describes the level of date/time precision (via Eventor) given to a particular Factor. Example precisions include: Year, Day, Second, etc.

data.name: EventorType
data.value: Provides temporal significance (via Eventor) for a particular Factor. Example types include: Start, Occur, Expected, etc.

data.name: FactorAssertion
data.value: Describes the type of information (and/or level of confidence) provided by a particular Factor. Example assertions include: Fact, Opinion, Guess, etc.

data.name: IdentorType
data.value: Provides a hint about the text (via Identor) that identifies a particular Factor. Example types include: Text, Key, etc.

data.name: LocatorType
data.value: Provides spatial context and boundaries (via Locator) for a particular Factor. Example types include: Earth Coordinate, Mars Coordinate, Relative 3D Position, etc.

data.name: MemberType
data.value: Describes the level of access and control given to a particular Member. Example types include: !Member, Admin, Data Provider, etc.

data.name: VectorRange
data.value: Provides meaning (using relatively-positioned points/labels) across the numerical range of a particular VectorType. Example ranges include: Negative Numeric, Full Agreement, Positive Favorability, etc.

data.name: VectorRangeLevel
data.value: A relatively-positioned point which provides meaning to a numerical range. Example levels include: Maximum, Somewhat Disagree, Mostly Favorable, etc.

data.name: VectorType
data.value: Provides meaning and boundaries (via Vector) for a numeric value given to a particular Factor. Example types include: Full Percentage, Standard Agreement, Opposable Favorability, etc.

data.name: VectorUnit
data.value: Provides a unit of measurement for the numeric value of a particular Vector. Example units include: Metre, Second, Byte, etc.

data.name: VectorUnitPrefix
data.value: Provides a level of magnitude for the numeric value of a particular Vector. Example unit prefixes include: Kilo, Nano, Gibi, etc.
